snippet.textDisplay:
Coke studio will have to find its own voice, rooted in its own traditions and Carnatic music is the glacier from which Hindustani flows. By leaving the south Indians out, coke studio has unwittingly left out a huge opportunity for finding original sound. This Punjabi obsession of the Punjabi is costing the nation it's own sound. 

Punjab has tremendous potential, but that national sound of India is well beyond Punjabi and it's time for coke studio to get much better curators. 

Selecting the selector as usual is the hardest part. 

Look at sriram iyer and mathangi. See what they bring to the table. Original sound!

And I'm not even getting into a.r.rahmam and all things glorious.

snippet.textDisplay: The taal changes in this song are really interesting. You can follow the time signature transitions whenever the drummer hits his snares twice. Rock/Blues riffs are used here to weave them together. Once the users get a feel for this, maybe the producer will try Jazz or some or other technique. This song is a good example of how difficult it is to fuse a simple sufi style with the clockwork precision Carnatic requires.
